WEBVTT

00:08.860 --> 00:13.040
Coming up next is the Science Fiction Radio Show, so stay with us.

00:30.000 --> 00:35.100
This is the Science Fiction Radio Show, a commentary on science fiction and fantasy.

00:38.080 --> 00:39.680
And here are your hosts.

00:44.240 --> 00:45.500
This is David Carson.

00:45.800 --> 00:46.580
And Daryl Lane.

00:46.860 --> 00:50.260
For 20 years, Roger Zelazny has been writing science fiction and fantasy.

00:50.640 --> 00:53.460
He tells us why and how he became a science fiction writer.

00:54.400 --> 00:55.440
Well, it's a funny thing.

00:55.440 --> 01:05.580
I was originally a reader of science fiction from about the age of 11 through high school.

01:06.240 --> 01:09.360
And during that period, I did write a lot of science fiction stories, which I tried

01:09.360 --> 01:11.700
to sell, but I was like my early teens.

01:12.120 --> 01:17.300
And I didn't really meet any success at that point.

01:17.980 --> 01:24.000
And I decided actually before that that I wanted to be a writer.

01:24.900 --> 01:31.080
I wasn't necessarily science fiction that I had in mind, though it was science fiction

01:31.080 --> 01:33.880
stories that I was writing during the period I was reading them.

01:34.580 --> 01:38.220
When I went to college, I stopped reading science fiction, just concentrated on the

01:38.220 --> 01:39.200
material I had there.

01:39.280 --> 01:41.660
And I wrote poetry actually, exclusively.

01:43.160 --> 01:47.760
I decided that I was going to start writing again as soon as I got out of college and

01:47.760 --> 01:48.500
had some time.

01:49.180 --> 01:55.180
And at that point, I wasn't absolutely certain what it was that I would try writing, but

01:55.180 --> 02:06.920
when the opportunity finally presented itself in early 1962, I decided it might be easier

02:06.920 --> 02:12.900
for me to break into science fiction since I had read so much of it in the past, knew

02:12.900 --> 02:13.400
the area.

02:13.400 --> 02:15.560
So I decided I'd try there first.

02:15.840 --> 02:19.620
And I went out and re-familiarized myself with science fiction.

02:21.980 --> 02:24.920
And then I began writing and submitting the stories.

02:25.220 --> 02:29.120
And after about six or seven weeks, I sold my first one.

02:29.460 --> 02:33.300
And I sold 16 others that year.

02:33.540 --> 02:35.420
So I stayed with it.

02:36.360 --> 02:41.360
Zelazny has always been recognized as a stylist, a writer to whom craftsmanship is important.

02:41.800 --> 02:45.000
His characters have depth, and his prose is coherent and flexible.

02:45.460 --> 02:45.640
Right.

02:46.120 --> 02:47.420
And that's an important point to make.

02:47.820 --> 02:51.500
Science fiction has traditionally been a field in which style and character were secondary

02:51.500 --> 02:52.580
to plot and idea.

02:52.940 --> 02:57.180
Zelazny's college background in his major field of study, English, may have had some

02:57.180 --> 02:58.220
influence on his writing.

02:59.200 --> 03:01.760
As an undergraduate, I was a psychology major.

03:03.020 --> 03:07.700
And I decided I did not really want to work as a psychologist.

03:07.700 --> 03:13.120
And it occurred to me somewhere along the line that if I'm more simply going to be teaching

03:14.000 --> 03:20.180
and writing with the aim in mind of eventually writing full time, I might as well teach

03:20.180 --> 03:23.240
something that would be a little more fun than psychology.

03:23.240 --> 03:30.300
So I switched to English and took my graduate work in English and comparative literature.

03:31.600 --> 03:36.500
As a result of this background, Zelazny says, his stories had some characteristics not common

03:36.500 --> 03:37.860
to traditional science fiction.

03:38.580 --> 03:46.180
I suppose having grown up on the earlier sort of science fiction, the space opera, sort

03:46.180 --> 03:53.500
of thing of the 30s and 40s too, and the harder science stories of the 40s and some of the

03:53.500 --> 04:05.160
sociological science fiction of the 50s, and having a background in literature, I, there's

04:05.160 --> 04:09.440
a natural tendency, whether it's conscious or not, to want to do something different

04:10.000 --> 04:11.900
than things that had gone before.

04:12.840 --> 04:18.580
As a consequence, my stories, well the first ones were basically gimmick stories because

04:18.580 --> 04:21.120
it was the easiest way to break in.

04:21.240 --> 04:23.900
It was about all that I was capable of doing at the time.

04:24.060 --> 04:30.300
But when I began writing at greater length and when I was a bit sure of myself, I would

04:30.300 --> 04:31.480
think of the characters first.

04:31.480 --> 04:37.520
First, so the stories tended to have more, I suppose, in the way of psychological motivation

04:37.520 --> 04:39.640
rather than just external characterization.

04:42.040 --> 04:51.300
And my writing itself, possibly because of the years I spent writing poetry and reading

04:53.000 --> 05:01.460
general literature, tended to be a bit different from some of the earlier things which were

05:01.480 --> 05:03.380
kind of journalistic in character.

05:04.780 --> 05:06.900
More next time about Roger Zelazny.

