06:29.680 --> 06:35.220
This is the Science Fiction Radio Show, a commentary on science fiction and fantasy.

06:37.680 --> 06:39.720
And here are your hosts.

06:44.600 --> 06:45.460
This is David Carson.

06:45.680 --> 06:46.280
And Daryl Lane.

06:46.640 --> 06:50.580
Science Fiction authors sometimes write fantasy, and fantasy authors sometimes write science

06:50.580 --> 06:50.920
fiction.

06:51.360 --> 06:52.520
Roger Zelazny writes both.

06:52.940 --> 06:55.180
He talks about the differences between the two forms.

06:56.680 --> 06:58.620
I do make the distinction myself.

06:58.620 --> 07:06.120
In a science fiction story, everything I feel should be explainable in terms of natural

07:06.120 --> 07:10.960
laws, or extensions of natural laws as we understand them now.

07:12.180 --> 07:18.640
Whereas in a fantasy story, it's part of the rules of the game, so I feel there are

07:18.640 --> 07:25.560
no compunctions against invoking the supernatural or bringing in magic and things of that sort.

07:28.620 --> 07:34.120
And so basically a science fiction story, things are ultimately explainable in a fantasy

07:34.120 --> 07:34.600
story.

07:36.580 --> 07:39.860
They're explainable really in terms of something that isn't explainable.

07:40.440 --> 07:50.660
So you've got more, you've got the less rational background if you push things far

07:50.660 --> 07:51.820
enough in a fantasy story.

07:53.060 --> 07:56.580
So Zelazny says he writes some of his books so that they can be read either way.

07:57.860 --> 08:01.580
I also believe in mixing the two.

08:05.120 --> 08:10.620
Lord of Light, for instance, was a book where I intentionally wrote it to be taken two ways

08:10.620 --> 08:11.260
of fantasy.

08:12.280 --> 08:21.620
A fan could read it as a piece of fantasy, whereas a science fiction fan also had options

08:21.620 --> 08:22.600
available to him.

08:22.920 --> 08:29.560
Any single item which occurs in there, which is of an unusual nature, is that there's

08:29.560 --> 08:34.080
ultimately an explanation available for it if the person cares to use it.

08:34.600 --> 08:36.120
If he doesn't, that's fine too.

08:37.200 --> 08:39.680
Zelazny makes an interesting point about science fiction.

08:40.260 --> 08:44.800
He says that sometimes a science fiction story will become a fantasy story after a certain amount of time.

08:45.240 --> 08:49.180
And he uses one of his own stories, A Rose for Ecclesiastes, as an example.

08:50.820 --> 09:00.400
It's kind of funny too because I think the first story for which I became known was a piece called A Rose for Ecclesiastes.

09:05.800 --> 09:12.700
One of my reasons in writing this is because I was very fond of the earlier space operas and things like this,

09:12.780 --> 09:15.320
where they played John Carter of Mars.

09:15.320 --> 09:26.320
And I had always wanted to do something set on the Mars, which existed in these earlier stories.

09:26.440 --> 09:31.520
And I knew at the time I wrote it that it was scientifically impossible at that point.

09:31.600 --> 09:38.260
We already knew enough about Mars to know that the temperature was not the same as I had it in the story,

09:38.360 --> 09:40.800
that the atmosphere was not the same and so forth.

09:40.800 --> 09:44.820
But it was close enough to the point where this knowledge was just becoming current,

09:45.360 --> 09:49.000
that I could still get away with doing a thing like that.

09:49.240 --> 09:53.420
So I intentionally wrote that and wrote it in the fashion I did.

09:56.100 --> 09:58.960
I was a kind of exercise and nostalgia on my part.

09:59.060 --> 10:04.880
I always wanted to do a story set on that kind of Mars.

10:04.880 --> 10:08.320
And I knew that if I waited another year or so I wouldn't be able to.

10:09.240 --> 10:14.380
The same with Venus for my story, the doors of his face, the lamps of his mouth.

10:14.860 --> 10:20.420
At that point we already were aware that the surface temperature was about 900 degrees,

10:20.680 --> 10:26.660
but still there was this whole traditional body of science fiction literature,

10:26.820 --> 10:33.400
which had a vast, watery world, misty and so forth.

10:33.400 --> 10:38.660
I really had wanted to use at least once in my life, so I did those two stories

10:38.660 --> 10:40.740
as a kind of tribute to the earlier things.

10:42.760 --> 10:48.980
But then again I wrote them the way I was writing them rather than in the older style.

10:49.280 --> 10:55.120
So reading them now they'd have to be regarded as fantasy rather than science fiction

10:55.120 --> 11:01.300
because science has already demonstrated that those circumstances don't prevail.

