12:22.160 --> 12:27.660
This is the Science Fiction Radio Show, a commentary on science fiction and fantasy.

12:30.280 --> 12:32.120
And here are your hosts.

12:36.480 --> 12:37.700
This is David Carson.

12:38.040 --> 12:38.720
And Darrell Lane.

12:38.920 --> 12:42.200
Many science fiction and fantasy authors these days write novels and series

12:42.200 --> 12:44.960
in three, four and sometimes five book sets.

12:45.420 --> 12:49.480
Jack Shocker's Well World series or Elizabeth Lynn's trilogy The Chronicles of Tornor

12:49.480 --> 12:50.520
are two good examples.

12:50.960 --> 12:53.220
It's a commercially attractive idea for one thing.

12:53.640 --> 12:57.040
If readers like the first book, then there's a ready-made market for the following ones.

12:57.040 --> 13:01.720
And of course it also allows an author the scope to pursue a theme in greater depth and length

13:01.720 --> 13:02.980
than a single book would allow.

13:03.500 --> 13:06.160
And the extra depth can give an epic quality to the series.

13:06.800 --> 13:10.080
One of the best of the series is a set of five books by Roger Zelazny,

13:10.500 --> 13:13.820
a science fantasy adventure called simply The Amber Series.

13:14.600 --> 13:18.440
The first volume is entitled Nine Princes and Amber, and it was published in 1971.

13:19.520 --> 13:25.320
The other four, The Guns of Avalon, Sign of the Unicorn, The Hand of Oberon, and the Courts of Chaos.

13:26.220 --> 13:28.980
Zelazny calls the book Something Beside Science Fantasy.

13:29.860 --> 13:34.000
Whenever I try anything of this sort, I try to give it an extra twist is what it is.

13:34.280 --> 13:44.760
Basically, I look at it myself as a kind of heroic fantasy with a few variations that don't usually occur in that sort of literature.

13:45.840 --> 13:49.620
One of the variations Zelazny develops in the books is what's called the pattern.

13:50.500 --> 13:58.740
It is a kind of archetypal design which exists in the real world,

13:59.280 --> 14:09.220
amber of which our own earth and a great variety of shadings and variations thereof exist.

14:11.440 --> 14:16.020
Amber is the real world earth and the others are referred to as shadow.

14:16.700 --> 14:27.720
Our shadow in the story is the background, the basis of reality in amber is this design called the pattern,

14:27.960 --> 14:38.380
which was inscribed by an ancestor of the clan about whom the story is told.

14:38.380 --> 14:47.480
Only a person of the blood of the royal family of amber is able to walk this pattern and not be destroyed by it.

14:47.860 --> 14:54.700
And in the course of walking the pattern at some point in his early life,

14:57.540 --> 15:02.380
amberite acquires the ability to walk through the various shadow worlds,

15:03.800 --> 15:12.380
which surround amber so that he can travel through an infinity of possibilities to virtually any world he desires.

15:13.460 --> 15:16.600
The basic plot of the series consists of a struggle for the throne of amber,

15:16.920 --> 15:22.320
and in the process our earth is threatened with destruction since we are only a shadow of the real world of amber.

15:23.380 --> 15:27.700
In the struggle the main character Corwin keeps traveling between our earth and amber.

15:27.700 --> 15:31.800
Technology doesn't work in amber so the people there fight with swords and magic.

15:32.040 --> 15:36.720
For this reason the books are called science fantasy or as Zelazny said, heroic fantasy.

15:37.240 --> 15:42.100
They've been very popular too. Zelazny says the readers have responded enthusiastically.

15:42.980 --> 15:46.940
I have gotten more fan letters on the amber books than anything else I've ever written.

15:49.340 --> 15:54.620
There was a period of a couple of years there where I was getting several letters a week on the amber books.

15:55.380 --> 15:59.800
The narrative was concluded with an exciting climax in the fifth book, The Courts of Chaos.

16:00.340 --> 16:04.800
Because of the wide reader response though, and because there were some unanswered questions in that last book,

16:05.260 --> 16:07.080
a sixth novel on amber is a possibility.

16:08.240 --> 16:13.120
There is possibly a sixth one. I have made no commitments. I do not have a plot,

16:13.520 --> 16:18.720
but I've been talking about it and thinking about it, publisher.

16:21.560 --> 16:27.940
It is possible when I get a few things out of the way that I'm writing now that I might go on into a sixth one.

16:29.460 --> 16:36.400
But so far as the five books that now exist are concerned, that story is told.

16:36.980 --> 16:44.720
That was the story I had in mind. Anything which would continue, the series would probably take off in a new direction.

16:44.860 --> 16:47.400
It could possibly be from another character's point of view.

16:47.400 --> 16:50.180
More about Roger Zelazny next time.

