18:27.160 --> 18:31.120
One of the more interesting time travel books in recent years is Roadmarks by Roger Zelazny.

18:31.480 --> 18:34.080
Though time travel is one of the traditional science fiction themes,

18:34.460 --> 18:36.320
Zelazny doesn't often write that type of story.

18:37.200 --> 18:44.560
I have always attempted to avoid time travel stories because I don't like the paradoxes involved.

18:45.340 --> 18:53.300
In fact, the only thing I can think of that I had done in the past was a short story called Divine Madness.

18:54.960 --> 19:01.020
I said that I really wouldn't write a time travel story unless I came up with a new gimmick.

19:05.280 --> 19:15.300
For Roadmarks, I thought I had something in the image of time considered as a superhighway.

19:17.460 --> 19:25.920
Without the paradoxes, in an Everett Wheeler parallel world situation,

19:26.680 --> 19:34.740
it was really the image of the road that fascinated me and led to my writing that particular book.

19:35.640 --> 19:41.000
Time is conceived as a superhighway in Roadmarks, with the exits leading to different eras throughout time.

19:41.520 --> 19:45.720
Zelazny has an interesting story to tell regarding the origin of the idea behind Roadmarks.

19:46.280 --> 19:53.080
I got the idea for that book here in New Mexico really one Sunday.

19:53.080 --> 20:02.600
I was just out for a drive and I-25, which was a nice highway type road,

20:03.840 --> 20:06.920
took a turn off and drove for a few minutes.

20:07.260 --> 20:13.100
The road rapidly degenerated until, with a matter of minutes, I was on a dirt road

20:13.560 --> 20:17.580
and I passed through a place that I couldn't even find on the map.

20:17.580 --> 20:27.320
It was a little village where there was a horse pulling a wagon and no overhead electrical lines in sight.

20:28.360 --> 20:33.620
It was almost as if I had driven back through time into the 19th century.

20:33.740 --> 20:41.220
There were log buildings and somewhere around there something started to click.

20:41.220 --> 20:46.100
As I drove back again on the road and improved until finally I was on the superhighway,

20:46.320 --> 20:56.580
I started working out just the mechanisms for the idea of driving through time, which I used in Roadmarks.

20:57.500 --> 21:04.060
Actually by the time I got home I had a number of the situations worked out and I sat down and began writing it.

21:10.760 --> 21:13.260
The protagonist is a man named Red Dorokin.

21:13.820 --> 21:16.640
He travels up and down this highway of time in a battered old pickup.

21:17.080 --> 21:20.120
And when he's not trying to avoid and outwit some assassins who are after him,

21:20.480 --> 21:23.140
he's running guns to the Greeks back in the past at Marathon.

21:23.700 --> 21:26.700
And there's something else in the book that's a recurring motif or symbol,

21:27.220 --> 21:29.520
huge dragons that float above the road occasionally.

21:29.520 --> 21:33.780
Their function is not clear, but they seem to have some responsibility for the road.

21:34.180 --> 21:43.100
They were simply to represent the dark forces, which I tend to bring in any fantasy novel.

21:43.700 --> 21:52.160
In a story like this, there has to be a point where you have to ultimately reach something that's basically unexplainable.

21:53.060 --> 21:57.320
Namely, where did the road come from and how did it come to function, the way that it did.

21:57.320 --> 22:03.480
And in making a decision on that, I could go either way.

22:03.580 --> 22:08.940
I could find some science fiction trappings and explain it,

22:09.240 --> 22:17.060
or I could leave it intentionally, something shadowy and with a more fantasy background.

22:17.220 --> 22:22.440
If I did that, I decided I needed some symbol to invoke as an ultimate creator of the road,

22:22.580 --> 22:26.080
hence the dragons, and then they're tie-in with Red.

22:26.920 --> 22:30.820
Roadmarks published in 1981 is a different sort of time travel story,

22:31.300 --> 22:34.280
tending toward the fantasy rather than the science fiction end of the spectrum.

22:34.800 --> 22:38.280
And since Roger Zelazny is responsible for it, it's highly enjoyable.

22:38.960 --> 22:41.180
And we'll have more on Roger Zelazny on our next show.

